Dataset Description¶

Craigslist is the world's largest collection of used vehicles for sale, yet it's very difficult to collect all of them in the same place. I built a scraper for a school project and expanded upon it later to create this dataset which includes every used vehicle entry within the United States on Craigslist.¶

  1. url = Link to listing
  2. city = Craigslist region in which this listing was posted
  3. city_url = Link to region page
  4. price = Price of vehicle
  5. year = Year of vehicle
  6. manufacturer = Manufacturer of vehicle
  7. make = Make of vehicle
  8. condition = Condition of vehicle
  9. cylinders = Number of cylinders of vehicle
  10. fuelFuel = taken by vehicle
  11. odometer = Miles vehicle has been driven
  12. title_status = Title status of vehicle (e.g. clean - this vehicle has all legal documents. missing - these documents are missing)
  13. transmission = Transmission of vehicle
  14. VIN = Vehicle Identification Number
  15. drive = Drive of vehicle
  16. size = Size of vehicle
  17. type = Vehicle type
  18. paint_color = Color of vehicle
  19. image_url = Link to image of vehicle
  20. desc = Listing description provided by owner
  21. lat = Latitude of vehicle (not precise but very close)
  22. long = Longitude of vehicle (not precise but very close)

Categorical Missing Value Imputation with Mode¶

In [12]:
datafull['manufacturer'].fillna(datafull['manufacturer'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['cylinders'].fillna(datafull['cylinders'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['drive'].fillna(datafull['drive'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['make'].fillna(datafull['make'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['state_code'].fillna(datafull['state_code'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['county_name'].fillna(datafull['county_name'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['fuel'].fillna(datafull['fuel'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['transmission'].fillna(datafull['transmission'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['title_status'].fillna(datafull['title_status'].mode()[0], inplace=True)
datafull['paint_color'].fillna(datafull['paint_color'].mode()[0], inplace=True)

Numerical Missing Value Imputation with Median¶

I choose median as the imputer because median is a robust method to avoid the effect of outlier.

In [13]:
datafull.fillna(datafull.median(), inplace=True)

Numerical Variable¶

Pearson Correlation Plot¶

This Method can be used to see the relationship between numerical variables

In [22]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt 
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np
#create correlation with hitmap

#create correlation
corr = datafull[Numerical.columns].corr(method = 'pearson')

#convert correlation to numpy array
mask = np.array(corr)

#to mask the repetitive value for each pair
mask[np.tril_indices_from(mask)] = False
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (15,12))
fig.set_size_inches(20,10)
sns.heatmap(corr, 
            mask = mask, 
            vmax = 0.9, 
            square = True, 
            annot = True)

Time Series Plot From The Average of Price each Year and Yearly Count of Cars User¶

In [141]:
f=plt.figure(figsize=(20,15))

f.add_subplot(2,1,1)
car_year=datafull[datafull['year']>1950]
#car_year['year']=pd.Categorical(car_year['year'])
ax3 = sns.countplot(car_year.year)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title("Count Of Car each Year");

f.add_subplot(2,1,2)
data_price=pd.DataFrame(datafull[['year','price']].groupby('year').mean()['price']).reset_index()
data_price_1900=data_price[data_price['year']>1950]
plt.bar(data_price_1900['year'],data_price_1900['price'])
plt.title("Average of Car Price each year ");

plt.show()

  • The first graph explain the distribution of car purchases each year. The second graph is the average price of car purchases each year.

  • From the first graph, it can be seen that car purchasing trends began to increase from 1998 and peaked in 2007, after that the trend began to decline until 2018

  • The second graph explains the average movement of car purchase prices from year to year. It can be seen that from 1950, car purchase prices tended to decline, but from 2000, car purchase prices began to rise and peak in 2014-2016

  • From the comparison of the two graphs above, it can be seen that in 2004-2008, car sales are high, but the purchase price of cars is low, it can be concluded that the lower the price of the car will increase the demand of the car

statecount = datafull.state_code.value_counts()
datamap = dict(type='choropleth',
            colorscale = 'Reds',
            locations = statecount.index,
            z = statecount,
            locationmode = 'USA-states',
            marker = dict(line = dict(color = 'rgb(255,255,255)',width = 2)),
            colorbar = {'title':"Cars listed per State"}
            ) 
layout = dict(title = 'Cars listed per State',
              geo = dict(scope='usa',
                         showlakes = True,
                         lakecolor = 'rgb(85,173,240)')
             )
choromap = go.Figure(data = [datamap],layout = layout)
iplot(choromap)
  • From the map of the distribution of cars above, it can be seen that the distribution of car sales has not been evenly distributed in the USA. Most cars are sold in California. From there it can be concluded that the demand for car users in USA is more concentrated in the USA.
